In a web application, the server doesn't have direct control over the client's browser, so it can't close a webpage directly. However, you can implement a feature where pressing 'q' on the keyboard sends a request to the server, and the server responds by redirecting the browser to another page or showing a message.

Here's a simple way to do this using JavaScript on the client side and Flask on the server side:

1. Add a JavaScript event listener for keypresses to your HTML page. If 'q' is pressed, send a request to a new Flask route, `/quit`.

```html
<script>
document.addEventListener('keypress', function(event) {
    if (event.key === 'q') {
        fetch('/quit');
    }
});
</script>
```

2. In your Flask app, add a new route that handles the `/quit` URL. You can make it return a simple message or redirect the user to another page.

```python
@app.route('/quit')
def quit():
    return "You pressed 'q'. The page will now close."
```

Remember, this won't actually close the webpage, but it will replace its content with the message "You pressed 'q'. The page will now close." If you want to redirect to another page, you can use `flask.redirect` instead of returning a string.

Note: This solution assumes that you have control over the HTML content of the webpage. If the webpage is not under your control, you won't be able to add the JavaScript code to it.

